    <li id="fn:9" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>James‚Äôs <em>World Revolution</em> is redolent with references to ‚Äúthe
dictatorship of the proletariat‚Äù (100, 103, 105); ‚Äúthe
petty-bourgeoisie and the proletariat‚Äù (84); ‚Äúthe revolutionary
proletariat‚Äù (106); ‚Äúthe Russian proletariat‚Äù (122); ‚Äúthe
international proletariat‚Äù (124); ‚Äúthe Socialist proletariat‚Äù (163);
‚Äúthe advanced proletariat‚Äù (232); ‚Äúthe great German proletariat‚Äù
(312); and so on. While the many deployments of the concept in
<em>World Revolution</em> clearly serve to drive home the revolutionary,
Trotskyist argument of James‚Äôs history, the fact that James thought
it unnecessary to define the term with any specificity in 1937 is
nonetheless undoubtedly symptomatic, in the full Althusserian sense
of the term. Symptomatic, that is to say, of what is arguably a
traditional, Leninist interpretation of Marx and <em>Capital</em> more
specifically as a critique made from the standpoint of labor rather
than that of capitalism as a social totality. On the latter, see
Moishe Postone, <em>Time, Labor, and Social Domination: A
Reinterpretation of Marx‚Äôs Critical Theory</em> (Cambridge: Cambridge
University Press, 1993). James‚Äôs critique of global capitalist
imperialism, for all its brilliance, arguably remained a political
critique of class-based exploitation that rarely if ever drew on the
theoretical insights of Marx‚Äôs categorial critique of political
economy. James will write in this vein, in his 1944 essay ‚ÄúThe
American People in ‚ÄòOne World,‚Äô‚Äù that ‚Äúthe laws of dialectics are to
be traced not in metaphysical abstractions‚Ä¶but in economic
development and the rise, maturity, and decline of different social
classes within the expansion and constriction of the capitalist
world market‚Äù (McLemee and Le Blanc, <em>C. L. R. James and
Revolutionary Marxism</em>, 175). On James‚Äôs original appropriation of
traditional, Leninist-humanist Marxism, which Anthony Bogues terms
‚Äúblack Marxism,‚Äù see Anthony Bogues, <em>Caliban‚Äôs Freedom: The Early
Political Thought of C. L. R. James</em> (Chicago: Pluto, 1997), 6‚Äì9; on
the original and precocious brand of Marxist humanism developed by
the Johnson-Forrest Tendency, see 69‚Äì75: ‚ÄúWe [the members of the
Johnson-Forrest Tendency] were convinced on a re-examination of
Marx‚Äôs capital [<em>sic</em>],‚Äù observed James in 1947, ‚Äúthat the
solution to the economic ills of capitalism was the human solution‚Äù
(qtd. on 75).¬†<a href="#fnref:9" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:10" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>James, <em>World Revolution</em>, 70.¬†<a href="#fnref:10" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:11" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Ibid., 78‚Äì79.¬†<a href="#fnref:11" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
