    </li>
    <li id="fn:17" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Two of Marx‚Äôs many citations gleaned from Capital, vol. 1: ‚ÄúOne
might almost say that modern society lives at the expense of the
proletarians, on the portion of the wages of labour which it
withdraws from their pockets‚Äù (Sismondi, qtd. on 207); ‚ÄúThe
proletarian, by selling his labour for a definite quantity of the
means of subsistence (<em>approvisionnement</em>), renounces all claim to a
share in the product‚Äù (Charbuliez, qtd. on 718). J. C. L. Simonde de
Sismondi, <em>√âtudes sur l‚Äô√©conomie politique</em>, vol. 1 (Bruxelles:
Soci√©t√© Typographique Belge, 1837), 1:24; Antoine-Elis√©e Charbuliez,
<em>Richesse ou pauvret√©</em> (Paris: A. Le Gallois, 1841), 14.¬†<a href="#fnref:17" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:18" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>That one finds in <em>Capital</em> differing, even contradictory, uses and
definitions of the concept <em>proletariat</em> is not surprising, given
the often rough and unfinished nature of its three volumes. While it
is well known that after Marx‚Äôs death, Engels constructed volumes 2
and 3 for publication from various drafts Marx left in his papers,
even volume 1‚Äîthe publication of which Marx oversaw through its
second, revised German edition and first French translation
(1872‚Äì75)‚Äîbears no final form; Marx intended and made notes for a
further complete revision of it in 1881 (which he never carried
out). What we know as volume 1 is a bricolage Engels made of the
second German edition of 1872 and the French edition of 1872‚Äì75.
While the first draft of volume 1 from 1863 is lost (the
<em>Grundrisse</em> of 1857‚Äì58 is not, properly speaking, a draft of
<em>Capital</em> but a mass of preparatory notes that Marx termed an
‚Äúinquiry‚Äù [<em>Forschungsweise</em>]), the first German edition of 1867
as well as Marx‚Äôs notes for his intended 1881 revision contain many
important formulations and developments of his demonstration (in
particular, a radically different presentation of the key first
chapter on the value-form) absent from Engels‚Äôs posthumous
‚Äúdefinitive edition.‚Äù In fact, attention to the totality of Marx‚Äôs
drafts, notebooks, and letters from 1857 to 1881, gradually becoming
available in the definitive MEGA^2^ edition of Marx and Engels‚Äôs
works, leads to the conclusion, in Michael Heinrich‚Äôs words, that
‚Äúin a strict sense, a three-volume work ‚ÄòCapital‚Äô written by Marx
does not really exist‚Ä¶.There is no clear difference between drafts
and the final work‚Äîwe have only differently developed drafts of a
shifting, unfinished and incomplete project.‚Äù Michael Heinrich,
‚ÄúReconstruction or Deconstruction? Methodological Controversies
about Value and Capital, and New Insights from the Critical
Edition,‚Äù in Riccardo Bellofiore and Roberto Finneschi, eds.,
<em>Re-reading Marx: New Perspectives after the Critical Edition</em>
(London: Palgrave, 2009), 96. If, as Heinrich shows, it is the case
that these various iterations of Marx‚Äôs project reveal distinct and
ambivalent understandings of such key concepts as ‚Äúvalue‚Äù and
‚Äúlabor-power,‚Äù it is hardly surprising that this should be the case
for concepts of lesser importance to Marx‚Äôs categorial critique,
such as ‚Äúproletariat.‚Äù Moreover, here I am only considering the
standard English edition of <em>Capital</em>, vols. 1‚Äì3. Undoubtedly, there
remain to be discovered further variations in Marx‚Äôs
conceptualization of the ‚Äúproletariat‚Äù in the voluminous editions,
drafts, correspondence, and notes of the MEGA^2^.¬†<a href="#fnref:18" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:19" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>‚ÄúThe other classes decay and disappear in the face of large-scale
industry, the proletariat is its most characteristic product‚Äù (Marx,
<em>Capital</em>, 1:930).¬†<a href="#fnref:19" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:20" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>‚ÄúThe workers have been turned into proletarians, and their means
of labour into capital, as soon as the capitalist mode of production
stands on its own feet‚Äù (Marx, <em>Capital</em>, 1:928).¬†<a href="#fnref:20" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:21" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Marx, <em>Capital</em>, 1:764n1. By ‚ÄúRoscherian fancy,‚Äù Marx is
referring to Wilhelm Roscher, author of the 1858 volume <em>Die
Grundlagen der National√∂konomie</em>.¬†<a href="#fnref:21" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:22" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Adding to our uncertainty, Marx at one point even seems to
distinguish this ‚Äúfree‚Äù proletarian from wage labor‚Äîin time, space,
and nature: ‚ÄúWe have considered the forcible creation of a class of
free and rightless proletarians, the bloody discipline that turned
them into wage-labourers‚Äù (<em>Capital</em>, 1:905).¬†<a href="#fnref:22" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:23" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Marx, <em>Capital</em>, 1:896. Marx‚Äôs famous historical example is that
of the Scottish Crofters, the dispossession of whom created a labor
‚Äúreserve army,‚Äù one willing and indeed forced subsequently to take
on wage labor for their very survival. Similarly, he writes of the
Italian case: ‚ÄúIn Italy, where capitalist production developed
earliest, the dissolution of serfdom also took place earlier than
elsewhere. There the serf was emancipated before he had acquired any
prescriptive right to the soil. His emancipation at once transformed
him into a ‚Äòfree‚Äô proletarian, without any legal rights, and he
found a master ready and waiting for him in the towns‚Äù (<em>Capital</em>,
1:876). On the centrality of such transformations of property rights
for the imposition of capitalism, see Ellen Meiksins Wood, <em>The
Origin of Capitalism: A Longer View</em> (1999; repr., New York: Verso,
2017). Wood argues convincingly that the essential factor in the
imposition of capitalism as a social form is the transformation of
property rights. More specifically, this transformation made
inaccessible to the impoverished classes (such as the Scottish
Crofters) the basic amenities essential for survival, such as food
and shelter. Cast out by the Scottish Lords from their secular
homesteads as rightless, ‚Äúfree‚Äù proletarians (in Marx‚Äôs example),
they were forced to accept the contractual conditions of capitalist
wage labor in, for example, the Glasgow shipyards in order to
purchase the means of survival and their reproduction on the market
with these wages.¬†<a href="#fnref:23" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:24" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Marx, <em>Capital</em>, 1:897.¬†<a href="#fnref:24" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:25" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>On the 1790s Les Cayes Maroon communes, see Carolyn Fick, <em>The
Making of Haiti: The Saint-Domingue Revolution from Below</em>
(Knoxville: University of Tennessee Press, 1990). In terms perfectly
coherent with Marx‚Äôs analysis of primitive accumulation, Rosamunde
Renard describes this historical process in post-1848 Martinique and
Guadeloupe, where the commodification of the basic means of survival
and reproduction (along with the imposition of various mandatory
taxes and employment requirements) effectively forced former slaves
(despite various and unrelenting resistance) to accept the new
conditions of contractual wage labor on the plantations: ‚ÄúThose
ex-slaves who continued to do plantation work did not do so
voluntarily in many instances. The ex-slaves incurred expenses
unknown to the slave. Food, medical bills, clothing, rents‚Äîall
wholly or partly supplied by the plantation before emancipation‚Äîwere
now their personal responsibility. Moreover the plantocracy and the
administration increased these expenses even more in the attempt to
create an artificial need for money wages so that the blacks would
be forced to work on the plantations.‚Äù Rosamunde Renard, ‚ÄúLabor
Relations in Martinique and Guadeloupe, 1848‚Äì1870,‚Äù <em>Journal of
Caribbean History</em> 26, no. 1 (1992): 39.¬†<a href="#fnref:25" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:26" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>To further develop this argument, the distinction I am presenting
between James‚Äôs linear, developmental understanding of the relation
of slavery to capitalism and Marx‚Äôs binary, either/or analysis of
the concept of mode of production should be confronted as well with
James‚Äôs appropriation of Trotsky‚Äôs notion of combined and uneven
development. In this view, plantation slavery would constitute not a
barbaric remnant but a variegated element in the overdetermined
complex of Atlantic modernity. Such a view, however (and this is the
point of the present analysis), by simply positing ‚Äúslavery‚Äù as a
differential element within an equally underdefined totality
(‚Äúcapitalist modernity‚Äù), continues to put forth the question of the
precise, adequate analytical distinction between slavery and
capitalism. On James‚Äôs appropriation and deployment of Trotsky‚Äôs
concept of combined and uneven development, see Bill Schwarz, ‚ÄúHaiti
and Historical Time,‚Äù in Forsdick and H√∏gsbjorg, ‚ÄúThe Black
Jacobins‚Äù Reader, 99‚Äì102. On uneven development, see Bruno Bosteels,
‚ÄúReading Capital from the Margins: Notes on the Logic of Uneven
Development,‚Äù in Nick Nesbitt, ed., <em>The Concept in Crisis: Reading
‚ÄúCapital‚Äù Today</em> (Durham, NC: Duke University Press, 2017), 113‚Äì65.¬†<a href="#fnref:26" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:27" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>The famous chapters on primitive accumulation are the exception
that proves the rule, insofar as they are excurses to Marx‚Äôs object
of analysis, placed precisely after volume 1‚Äôs analysis of the
capitalist mode of production, despite the fact that historically
the events they discuss occur prior to the development of capitalism
in its high-industrial form.¬†<a href="#fnref:27" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:28" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Marx, <em>Capital</em>, 1:327.¬†<a href="#fnref:28" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:29" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Among the key theoretical distinctions Marx makes in his critique
of political economy is that between the production of wealth (in
the form of use values), exchange value (manifest in the form of
prices), and value itself. This fundamental theoretical insight not
only marks Marx‚Äôs decisive break with Ricardian value theory (Marx
was not a Left Ricardian) but remained as well a distinction
generally overlooked by the productivist orientation of traditional,
Leninist Marxism such as that professed, in singular fashion, to be
sure, by James. On this founding theoretical distinction of Marx‚Äôs
critique‚Äîdeveloped from the very first paragraph of <em>Capital</em>‚Äîand
its invisibility in traditional Marxism, see Postone, <em>Time, Labor,
and Social Domination</em>, 7‚Äì15. On the concept of Left Ricardianism‚Äîthat is, the failure to clearly distinguish wealth from value and the consequent promotion of the redistribution of that wealth rather than the destruction of the capitalist mode of production‚Äîsee Patrick Murray, ‚ÄúThe Illusion of the Economic: The Trinity Formula and the ‚ÄòReligion of Everyday Life,‚Äô‚Äù in Martha Campbell and Geert Reuten, eds., <em>The Culmination of Capital: Essays on Volume III of Marx‚Äôs Capital</em> (New York: Palgrave 2002), 250‚Äì52.¬†<a href="#fnref:29" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:30" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Quoted in Josette Fallope, <em>Esclaves et citoyens: Les noirs √† la
