    </li>
    <li id="fn:41" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>On the methodology of <em>Capital</em> as a form-based, categorial‚Äîas
opposed to historical or empiricist‚Äîanalysis of capitalism
(specifically, as what Marx calls ‚Äúvalue-form analysis‚Äù), see
Postone, <em>Time, Labor, and Social Domination</em>, 123‚Äì44; Juan
I√±igo-Carrera, ‚ÄúMethod: From the <em>Grundrisse</em> to <em>Capital</em>,‚Äù in
Riccardo Bellofiore, Guido Starosta, and Peter D. Thomas, eds., <em>In
Marx‚Äôs Laboratory: Critical Interpretations of the ‚ÄúGrundrisse‚Äù</em>
(Chicago: Haymarket, 2014), 43‚Äì70; and Riccardo Bellofiore, ‚ÄúThe
Multiple Meanings of Marx‚Äôs Value Theory,‚Äù <em>Monthly Review</em>, 1 April
2018,
<a href="https://monthlyreview.org/2018/04/01/the-multiple-meanings-of-marxs-value-theory/">https://monthlyreview.org/2018/04/01/the-multiple-meanings-of-marxs-value-theory/</a>.¬†<a href="#fnref:41" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:42" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Etienne Balibar, ‚ÄúOn the Basic Concepts of Historical
Materialism,‚Äù in Louis Althusser, Jacques Ranci√®re, Pierre Macherey,
Roger Establet, and Etienne Balibar, <em>Reading Capital: The Complete
Edition</em> (1965; repr., New York: Verso, 2017), 357‚Äì480. See also
Nick Nesbitt, ‚ÄúValue as Symptom,‚Äù in Nesbitt, <em>Concept in Crisis</em>,
229‚Äì79. I would argue that while <em>Reading Capital</em> invents a whole
range of singular concepts central to contemporary critical theory,
its various chapters also initiate, in 1965, this now-dominant
categorial or value-form reading of <em>Capital</em>, an approach to be
found in theorists from Postone, Robert Kurz, Elena Louisa Lange,
and Michael Heinrich to the outstanding series of publications of
the members of the International Symposium on Marxist Theory
(Bellofiore, Moseley, Tony Smith, et al.), and this despite the
silent disavowal or even active hostility toward Althusser‚Äôs thought
among the majority of these thinkers, a disavowal that is, I think,
symptomatic, to redeploy Althusser‚Äôs famous term, rather than
analytically coherent.¬†<a href="#fnref:42" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:43" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Balibar, ‚ÄúOn the Basic Concepts of Historical Materialism,‚Äù 392
(italics in original).¬†<a href="#fnref:43" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:44" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>The analytical apprehension of the criteria distinguishing
slavery from industrial capitalism such as I am proposing here does
not ignore, but in fact necessarily precedes and enables, the
obviously more complicated problem of the actual historical
transition between these two modes of production (in colonial
France, globally, etc.). While such an examination lies beyond the
scope of this essay, it might begin, as I suggested above regarding
the 1848 abolition process, by addressing historically the
implications of the temporal asynchronicity and overdetermined
complexity posited in Balibar‚Äôs analysis of the problem of
transition. See Alberto Toscano, ‚ÄúTransition Deprogrammed,‚Äù <em>SAQ</em>
113, no. 4 (2014): 761‚Äì75. For a rich account of the archival
material describing the phenomenal unfolding of this transition in
1840s Guadeloupe in its multiple dimensions (economic, political,
social, moral, etc.), see Fallope, <em>Esclaves et citoyens</em>.¬†<a href="#fnref:44" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:45" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Note that as with Marx‚Äôs <em>Capital</em> itself, the order of
exposition of Balibar‚Äôs analysis is analytical rather than
empiricist or historicist. To proceed from the enabling legal
framework for the capitalist mode of production to the key factors
whose particular arrangement determines its nature is to follow the
logic of a structural presentation with no isomorphic relation to the
historical, empirical supersession of capitalism over various
precapitalist modes of production such as feudalism and plantation
slavery.¬†<a href="#fnref:45" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:46" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>‚ÄúMarx‚Äôs concept cannot be made to coincide with the categories of
a sociology which, for its part, proceeds by the distribution and
adding together of levels‚Äîthe technological, the economic, the
legal, the social, the psychological, the political, etc.‚Äîand bases
its peculiar historical classifications on these distributions
(traditional societies and industrial societies, liberal societies
and centralized-totalitarian societies, etc.)‚Äù (Balibar, ‚ÄúOn the
Basic Concepts of Historical Materialism,‚Äù 398).¬†<a href="#fnref:46" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
