    <li id="fn:54" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Balibar, ‚ÄúOn the Basic Concepts of Historical Materialism,‚Äù 403.
‚ÄúAn organism of production,‚Äù Balibar continues, ‚Äúis now no longer
the union of a certain number of workers, it is a set of fixed
machines ready to receive any workers. From now on, ‚Äòa technique‚Äô is
a set of certain materials and instruments of labour, linked
together by a [general, social] knowledge of the physical
properties of each of them, and of their properties as a system‚Äù
(403).¬†<a href="#fnref:54" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:55" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Ibid., 406. And so, Balibar concludes, ‚ÄúThe movement from one
form to the other can be completely analysed: not as the mere
dissolution of a structure (the separation of the worker from the
means of labour [via so-called primitive accumulation]), but as
the transformation of one structure into another‚Ä¶.It is the forms of
the labour process which have changed‚Äù (407; emphasis mine).¬†<a href="#fnref:55" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:56" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Ibid., 407, 412. Balibar has recently offered an autocritique of
the structural logic of modes of production developed in his seminal
1965 text: ‚ÄúMy own text in <em>Reading Capital</em> was‚Äîat least this is
how I see it today‚Äîa perfect example of a blind alley into which a
blind use of the concept of structure was directed.‚Äù The object of
Balibar‚Äôs self-criticism is what he now sees as an indiscriminate
deployment of two contradictory senses of structure, that of the
social formation as a ‚Äústructured totality‚Äù possessing in any
historical case a particular and characteristic ‚Äúinvariant,‚Äù
combined with a contradictory attempt to think structure as ‚Äúthe
description of the transformation from one figure to the second,‚Äù
or, in other words, to articulate ‚Äúthe laws of the transformation‚Äù
or transition between modes of production. In the present argument,
needless to say, I do not fully accept Balibar‚Äôs autocritique, with
the essential proviso that the analytical determination of the
actually distinctive elements in such a comparison (legal, economic)
do not constitute an end point but only the very beginning, a mere
but essential prolegomenon to the examination of the complexly
overdetermined and variegated phenomenon of the transition from
plantation slavery to industrial capitalism. Etienne Balibar,
‚ÄúTheory and Politics in the Thought of Louis Althusser: An Interview
with Etienne Balibar by Petr Ku≈æel,‚Äù 2017; courtesy of Petr Ku≈æel.¬†<a href="#fnref:56" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:57" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>That American plantation slavery became increasingly productive
of cotton due to various proto-Taylorist, rationalizing
transformations in labor practices and their analysis in no way
implies, in this light, that it consequently became increasingly
‚Äúcapitalist‚Äù in nature, as Rosenthal claims, since (in light of
Rosenthal‚Äôs explicit refusal to offer a coherent definition of
capitalism), in the terms of Marx‚Äôs analysis, the production of use
values such as cotton, unlike surplus value, is a transhistorical
anthropological practice in no way specific to capital (<em>Accounting
for Slavery</em>, 5‚Äì6).¬†<a href="#fnref:57" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:58" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>‚ÄúA scientific analysis‚Ä¶is possible only if we can grasp the inner
nature of capital, just as the apparent motions of the heavenly
bodies are intelligible only to someone who is acquainted with their
real motions, which are not perceptible to the senses‚Äù (Marx,
<em>Capital</em>, 1:433).¬†<a href="#fnref:58" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
